post_text:
To plan for when WSD is able to return to an in-person instructional format, we need parents/guardians to select their preferred model of instruction through the WSD Return to School Form which is due by Thursday, July 30. For more information, please refer to your email account (Aeries) for a letter from Beverlee Mathenia, Senior Executive Director, Educational Services.

Please complete one form per child in your family and include your child‚Äôs student ID number. The ID number can be found in the Aeries parent portal on the WSD website, or you may call (714) 894-7311 for assistance. Click on this link to access the form: https://forms.gle/yLhyCNGbM7AZTz3z6

The instructional models include:
‚Ä¢ A 100% virtual learning model with rigorous instruction and daily live interactions from WSD credentialed teachers
‚Ä¢ A daily in-person instruction or the traditional school model, with enhanced health and safety measures
‚Ä¢ A hybrid model (a combination of learning at home and school)
‚Ä¢ A self-paced, independent study program at home

post_text: The US Constitution requires population statistics to be made every 10 years. post_text: The US Constitution requires population statistics to be made every 10 years. Answering the 2020 Census is easy, safe and important, and at the same time plays a key role in shaping the future of our community. The U.S. Census Bureau 2020 helps establish congressional seats and votes, and it is the basis for allocating about $ 900 billion in federal funding that affects education, housing, security, safety and other important public services. Please fill out the survey here: https://my2020census.gov/

Please remember to tag your entries by this Friday.

In an effort to support families during school closures, WSD is offering grab-n-go school supplies for students. In the same fashion as the grab-n-go meals, families will pick up supplies following safe distance protocol.

From 3/30 until 4/8, WSD will distribute free school supplies to kids ages 2-14. WSD parents can register to receive these supplies by registering at http://www.wsdk8.us or https://forms.gle/qteG2SaLCjijTeqo9. Once signed up, parents will be called by district staff to make arrangements to pick up supplies. Last day to register is Friday, April 3. Last day for pick up is listed in attached pictures.‚Äù

This message is being on behalf of Dr. Cyndi Paik, Superintendent:

Dear WSD Staff,

We understand this an extremely difficult time for all of you and our local communities. The current COVID-19 crisis has presented all of us with unprecedented challenges as we make decisions that are in the best interest of our students, families, and our valued staff.

At this time, there are local districts that have chosen to close their schools. There will be an emergency meeting with the Board today at 3pm to make important decisions.

As you know, the safety of our students and staff will always remain our priority. We are committed to keeping you informed as we reach key decisions. To facilitate effective communication, it‚Äôs important that you closely monitor your WSD/Outlook email account for the latest information. Thank you for your understanding and support during this challenging time.



Sincerely,

Dr. Cyndi Paik

Superintendent

shared_text:
MARS.NASA.GOV
Name the Rover Contest

Senator Tom Umberg
October 15, 2019 at 2:21 PM ¬∑

Name the next Mars Rover!!üåéüöÄ

NASA and Future Engineers are inviting students Kindergarten through 12th grade to submit essays to name the future rover. The 2020 Mars rover will seek signs of past microbial life, collect surface samples as the first leg of a Mars Sample Return campaign, and test technologies to produce oxygen from the Martian atmosphere to prepare for future human missions.

The contest closes on November 1, 2019. I know that we have some creative young minds within our community!

shared_text:
NEWSROOM.OCDE.US
Westminster dedicates district office in honor of Mendez family and their landmark civil rights case
text:
NEWSROOM.OCDE.US
Westminster dedicates district office in honor of Mendez family and their landmark civil rights case

post_text: Last night was an historic moment as we dedicated the District Office to the Mendez Family in honor of their courageous fight for equity for all children in the landmark Mendez v. Westminster case. The 1947 ruling effectively ended segregation in California and later the nation. Sylvia Mendez and the Mendez Family were honored by state and local leaders including Senator Tom Umberg, OC Supervisor Andrew Do, Westminster Mayor Tri Ta and Westminster Council Member Sergio Contreras.
text: Last night was an historic moment as we dedicated the District Office to the Mendez Family in honor of their courageous fight for equity for all children in the landmark Mendez v. Westminster case. The 1947 ruling effectively ended segregation in California and later the nation. Sylvia Mendez and the Mendez Family were honored by state and local leaders including Senator Tom Umberg, OC Supervisor Andrew Do, Westminster Mayor Tri Ta and Westminster Council Member Sergio Contreras.

shared_text:
Supervisor Andrew Do is at Westminster School District.
October 2, 2019 at 8:51 PM ¬∑ Westminster, CA ¬∑

I was humbled to be a part of today‚Äôs dedication of the Westminster School District‚Äôs office to La Familia Mendez, who won the landmark Orange County case Mendez, et al v. Westminster School District of Orange County, et al. In 1946, this case laid the foundation for school desegregation many years ahead of the civil rights movement. Through their advocacy and activism for equitable access, Sylvia Mendez and her family have become pillars of the education community.

Finley Computer Science Magnet Elementary School
May 28, 2019 at 7:19 PM ¬∑

Today, 4th graders from Mrs. Tarkanian‚Äôs class and 5th graders from Ms. Perry‚Äôs class went on a field trip to UCI.

First, students were taken on a guided tour of the campus, which provided a wonderful opportunity for students to see the university and learn about various programs and some history of the school.

Next, students visited the Working Memory and Plasticity Laboratory where they learned about working memory and how it is an essential system that underlies the performance of virtually all complex cognitive activities.

Last, they toured the UCI Applied Innovation Center. This center brings campus-based inventions and entrepreneurship together with Orange County's vibrant business community to support job creation and economic growth.

This field trip was fun, educational and inspiring for our Eagles!

Johnson Middle School
May 1, 2019 at 10:38 PM ¬∑

Johnson Middle School proudly hosted the first annual Special Olympics for our local elementary schools today. Students played soccer, hockey, bowling and bocce ball.

A very special shout out to Mrs. Marjorie Schubert , Mr. Jason Carey and Mr. Todd Canavan for organizing such fun games, activities and lunch for over 100 elementary students from our local elementary schools.

We had volunteers from administration, adaptive P.E., Down for Dance, speech pathology, psychologists, leadership, cheer and JMS students to help bring everything together for our student athletes.
Mr. Coatney‚Äôs class made 3D mini trophies for each class to take home and Mr. Schammann‚Äôs class came out to fly drones overhead to make it extra special.

What a fun day for all!
